00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:31.690
And I learned some
of it the hard way.

00:09:31.690 --> 00:09:33.320
But take a look at this map.

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:36.330
So the map here, the
countries in red-- I

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:37.967
say countries, even
though it's really

00:09:37.967 --> 00:09:40.726
just us and two tiny little
ones, Suriname and Papua New

00:09:40.726 --> 00:09:41.830
Guinea, tiny islands.

00:09:41.830 --> 00:09:44.090
The countries in
red are the ones

00:09:44.090 --> 00:09:46.985
that don't have paid
maternity leave programmed.

00:09:46.985 --> 00:09:48.610
We hear a lot of
complaints about this,

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:50.050
but no one ever talks about why.

00:09:50.050 --> 00:09:51.758
No one ever explains
where it comes from.

00:09:51.758 --> 00:09:55.060
Well, it all comes from the
exact same place as those ads.

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:56.750
It comes from the "Mad Men" era.

00:09:56.750 --> 00:09:58.780
This is when our new
work culture was created.

00:09:58.780 --> 00:10:00.360
We were coming out of the war.

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:02.260
We were creating
this new economy,

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:05.600
and this new economy was
built on work life balance.

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:09.136
And the balance was that men
stay at work all the time,

00:10:09.136 --> 00:10:10.796
and women stay
home all the time.

00:10:10.796 --> 00:10:12.960
It was this very
strict, genuine way

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:14.210
for making a new work culture.

00:10:14.210 --> 00:10:17.960
And a lot of us think that the
country has come a long way,

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:19.220
but it actually hasn't.

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:22.260
Our work structures were
built entirely in that era.

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:24.670
So what you have
all over the nation

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:27.069
are people who are still
running companies, who still

00:10:27.069 --> 00:10:28.360
believe that that's what it is.

00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:30.800
It's ingrained in us,
because it's been there now

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:31.720
for a few generations.

00:10:31.720 --> 00:10:33.850
And we don't think
twice about it.

00:10:33.850 --> 00:10:35.900
I have learned about this.

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:38.690
I've been covering this
throughout my career.

00:10:38.690 --> 00:10:39.463
I started at NPR.

00:10:39.463 --> 00:10:41.046
This is major little
background on me.

00:10:41.046 --> 00:10:41.780
I've covered big businesses.

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:43.400
I've covered around the world.

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:46.090
So this was me doing
fact checking on CNN.

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:48.700
And so what happened was when
I started wearing my glasses,

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:50.826
more and more people
started taking me seriously.

00:10:50.826 --> 00:10:52.950
So I got more and more
chance-- it's so ridiculous.

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:56.970
I started doing more chances
to do fact checking on CNN.

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:58.290
This is TV news for you.

00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:00.889
So all these politicians
from all sides.

00:11:00.889 --> 00:11:03.180
And the pundits would literally
say whatever they want,

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:04.406
anything; whatever they want.

00:11:04.406 --> 00:11:07.030
And they would get away with it,
and no one would correct them.

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:09.032
And that was a huge problem.

00:11:09.032 --> 00:11:10.240
So I was like, wait a second.

00:11:10.240 --> 00:11:11.930
Can we just start fact
checking these things?

00:11:11.930 --> 00:11:13.596
So I started fact
checking these things.

00:11:13.596 --> 00:11:15.680
And then I ended
up applying that

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:17.940
to the other, more
important part of my life.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:19.030
This is my career.

00:11:19.030 --> 00:11:22.760
But who I really am, in
a bigger way, is a dad.

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:23.760
That's number one to me.

00:11:23.760 --> 00:11:26.780
And becoming a father,
becoming a parent,

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:28.180
it's always usually dramatic.

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:30.220
But in my case, it was
exceptionally dramatic,

00:11:30.220 --> 00:11:33.920
in our case, because in
every one of our births,

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:35.090
we've had a wild story.

00:11:35.090 --> 00:11:36.710
This is my son; my first son.

00:11:36.710 --> 00:11:38.690
When he was two days
old, we found out

00:11:38.690 --> 00:11:42.590
that he had a heart defect,
but a very serious heart defect

00:11:42.590 --> 00:11:43.640
at that.

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:46.110
And so at seven days, this
is what he looked like.

00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:48.472
And I share this picture
because yes, it's horrifying,

00:11:48.472 --> 00:11:49.430
and it was a nightmare.

00:11:49.430 --> 00:11:51.890
But this is also
beautiful, because this

00:11:51.890 --> 00:11:53.480
is a story of humanity.

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:54.750
We adapt to survive.

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:55.830
This is what we do.

00:11:55.830 --> 00:11:58.730
This is why I care so much
about coming to businesses

00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:01.010
like Google, because
this spirit of innovation

00:12:01.010 --> 00:12:03.010
is how we come up
with stuff like this.

00:12:03.010 --> 00:12:04.461
It's how we fix things.

00:12:04.461 --> 00:12:06.710
It's also why I never listen
to cynics, because cynics

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:08.340
are the ones who
would say oh, we'll

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:11.690
never find a way to fix a tiny
little valve in a baby's heart.

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:13.870
Innovation, to
me, is everything.

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:15.790
And here is my kid a year later.

00:12:15.790 --> 00:12:16.600
They fixed it.

00:12:16.600 --> 00:12:18.469
So I'm constantly
reminded of how important

00:12:18.469 --> 00:12:20.760
it is to innovate, because
that's that human spark that

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:22.044
makes us who we are.

00:12:22.044 --> 00:12:23.210
So that was baby number one.

00:12:23.210 --> 00:12:24.620
Then with baby number
two we thought OK.

00:12:24.620 --> 00:12:26.762
This time, we'll have
relatively drama free birth.

00:12:26.762 --> 00:12:27.720
But that didn't happen.

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:30.760
So this time, my
wife and the baby

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:33.300
conspired to skip
labor altogether.

00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:35.500
She was three weeks
before her due date.

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:39.440
She fell to the floor and
couldn't say anything.

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:42.510
And suddenly, stuff started
coming out into my hands.

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:45.280
And then I saw his head,
but his eyes were closed,

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:46.600
and he wasn't moving.

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:48.720
And then I saw his neck
and the umbilical cord

00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:50.950
was wrapped around
his neck five times.

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:52.920
And then he entirely
came out into my hand.

00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:54.336
Now, he turned out
perfectly, too.

00:12:54.336 --> 00:12:55.340
Everything worked great.

00:12:55.340 --> 00:12:57.214
I'm going to share with
you all a little clip

00:12:57.214 --> 00:12:59.690
from my 9-1-1 call that day.

00:12:59.690 --> 00:13:01.980
I did this story more
than a year later,

00:13:01.980 --> 00:13:04.160
when I felt ready that
I could handle it.

00:13:04.160 --> 00:13:05.275
Here goes.

00:13:05.275 --> 00:13:08.005
This is where I had a segment
with my colleague, Sanjay

00:13:08.005 --> 00:13:08.060
Gupta.

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:08.190
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:13:08.190 --> 00:13:10.170
- --four hours of labor,
which are standard.

00:13:10.170 --> 00:13:11.628
With this one, all
of a sudden, she

00:13:11.628 --> 00:13:13.810
felt something, bent
over by the bed,

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:15.650
was feeling something
even more powerful,

00:13:15.650 --> 00:13:16.570
got down on the floor.

00:13:16.570 --> 00:13:16.810
Boom.

00:13:16.810 --> 00:13:18.130
Within a couple of minutes.

00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:19.639
-So no contractions beforehand?

00:13:19.639 --> 00:13:21.180
Because she knows
what it feels like.

00:13:21.180 --> 00:13:22.712
-She knows all the
steps very well,

00:13:22.712 --> 00:13:24.420
and she knows what
the feelings would be.

00:13:24.420 --> 00:13:27.180
This is incredibly unusual,
but it happened to her.

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:30.160
So she's down on the floor
and says, call an ambulance.

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:31.369
I get on the phone with 9/11.

00:13:31.369 --> 00:13:32.951
Here's a little clip
at what happened.

00:13:32.951 --> 00:13:33.596
-What do I do?

00:13:33.596 --> 00:13:34.720
I'm holding my baby's head.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:35.220
-OK, listen.

00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:36.910
I want you to support
the shoulders.

00:13:36.910 --> 00:13:37.410
-OK.

00:13:37.410 --> 00:13:39.261
-And hold the hips
and legs firmly.

00:13:39.261 --> 00:13:39.760
-OK.

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:42.670
-And remember, the baby will be
slippery, so don't drop it, OK?

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:43.270
-OK.

00:13:43.270 --> 00:13:44.960
-So is the baby completely
out, or just the head?

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:45.830
-No, just the head.

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:46.663
I'm seeing the head.

00:13:46.663 --> 00:13:47.727
It's all scrunched up.

00:13:47.727 --> 00:13:48.560
But it's not crying.

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:49.610
It's not making noise.

00:13:49.610 --> 00:13:50.930
Its eyes are shut.

00:13:50.930 --> 00:13:51.430
-OK.

00:13:51.430 --> 00:13:53.540
Have her to push hard
and get the baby out, OK?

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:54.480
-Got to push hard,
get the baby out.

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:55.479
Push hard, push hard.

00:13:55.479 --> 00:13:56.770
Oh my god, I'm holding my baby!

00:13:56.770 --> 00:13:58.700
It's an umbilical cord,
and there's something

00:13:58.700 --> 00:13:59.350
wrapped around its neck.

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:00.100
I'm taking it off.

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:00.730
-OK, listen.

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:02.667
Gently wipe the baby's
mouth and nose--

00:14:02.667 --> 00:14:03.250
-It's choking.

00:14:03.250 --> 00:14:04.450
It's choking on the chord.

00:14:04.450 --> 00:14:06.284
Breathe baby, breathe.

00:14:06.284 --> 00:14:07.200
Breathe baby, breathe.

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:08.241
I'm taking the chord off.

00:14:08.241 --> 00:14:10.751
-Let me give you a CPR
specialist for the baby, OK?

00:14:10.751 --> 00:14:11.250
-OK.

00:14:11.250 --> 00:14:11.880
The baby's breathing.

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:12.930
-Is the baby breathing?

00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:13.846
-Yeah, it's breathing.

00:14:13.846 --> 00:14:14.755
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:14:14.755 --> 00:14:15.921
JOSH LEVS: So it worked out.

00:14:15.921 --> 00:14:18.114
And you can see in there
that there were 84 seconds

00:14:18.114 --> 00:14:18.780
that we skipped.

00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:20.010
So there was a while
before we could

00:14:20.010 --> 00:14:21.280
see that he was breathing.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:24.589
This also gave me
a new commitment

00:14:24.589 --> 00:14:26.380
to and appreciation
for being a journalist,

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:28.710
because it was just so
random that I knew something.

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:30.876
What I didn't plan there
was that the 9-1-1 operator

00:14:30.876 --> 00:14:33.750
was telling me to tie off his
umbilical cord with a shoe

00:14:33.750 --> 00:14:34.699
lace.

00:14:34.699 --> 00:14:36.490
And I just happened to
know that you're not

00:14:36.490 --> 00:14:39.002
supposed to do that until you
can see the baby's breathing.

00:14:39.002 --> 00:14:40.460
So I always keep
in mind, you never

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:42.570
know what random fact
might actually help you.

00:14:42.570 --> 00:14:44.510
And that was because my
nephew had a traumatic birth.

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:46.260
And they thought he
wasn't going to make it.

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:48.060
But he did, because he
was still getting oxygen

00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:49.060
from the umbilical cord.

00:14:49.060 --> 00:14:51.010
So anyway, all of this,
what it did was it

00:14:51.010 --> 00:14:53.610
helped drill into
me my real values

00:14:53.610 --> 00:14:55.720
in this life, that family
is number one; that this

00:14:55.720 --> 00:14:59.690
is everything to me, that this
is always going to be the most

00:14:59.690 --> 00:15:00.911
important part of who I am.

00:15:00.911 --> 00:15:02.660
And especially after
my second son's birth

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:04.862
I stopped overworking,
and I started

00:15:04.862 --> 00:15:07.070
really looking for a work-life
balance, and work life

00:15:07.070 --> 00:15:08.320
integration, and the
right way to live,

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:10.060
and the right way to make
sure that I was there

00:15:10.060 --> 00:15:10.810
for all the moments.

00:15:10.810 --> 00:15:12.726
Because in that moment
when he was being born,

00:15:12.726 --> 00:15:14.570
it was so obvious to
me that nothing else

00:15:14.570 --> 00:15:19.540
matters except family, when
that's how you live your life.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:23.874
So after this, I started
talking to other dads

00:15:23.874 --> 00:15:25.290
about what they
were going through

00:15:25.290 --> 00:15:26.470
and what their experiences were.

00:15:26.470 --> 00:15:27.845
And this was also
around the time

00:15:27.845 --> 00:15:30.585
after the financial crisis,
when the economy fell apart.

00:15:30.585 --> 00:15:33.020
I like to call it a
financial fiasco, actually.

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:35.700
So I was interviewing
groups of dads.

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:38.279
And when Father's Day
came around in 2009

00:15:38.279 --> 00:15:39.820
it seemed like the
most obvious thing

00:15:39.820 --> 00:15:42.050
to me, to do a bunch of
segment talking to dads.

00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:42.810
And we talked about everything.

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:44.531
We talked about our
financial stresses,

00:15:44.531 --> 00:15:47.030
what we want for our kids, our
positions on gender equality,

00:15:47.030 --> 00:15:48.422
what we want in our careers.

00:15:48.422 --> 00:15:50.380
And the responses that
we got to these segments

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:51.940
were out of proportion.

00:15:51.940 --> 00:15:52.740
They were huge.

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:55.780
People were calling us, and
writing us, and e-mailing.

00:15:55.780 --> 00:15:58.530
And I started getting calls
from other media wanting

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:01.149
to interview me about being a
dad in the media who interviews

00:16:01.149 --> 00:16:03.190
dads, because no one had
seen anything like this.

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:05.650
And this forced me to
realize that no one had ever

00:16:05.650 --> 00:16:09.660
seen real dads, that
stereotypes still ruled the day.

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:13.040
So seeing dads talk about actual
issues that we care about.

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:14.690
It was just a new
idea to most people.

00:16:14.690 --> 00:16:16.148
All these parenting
segments on air

00:16:16.148 --> 00:16:17.980
had been about women;
maybe one token dad,

00:16:17.980 --> 00:16:20.090
maybe one token
stay-at-home dad.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:23.322
But having a group of dads
really open up was a new idea.

00:16:23.322 --> 00:16:25.780
So I made that a part of what
I did, and I started covering

00:16:25.780 --> 00:16:26.696
fatherhood a lot more.

00:16:26.696 --> 00:16:28.050
And then we thought, OK.

00:16:28.050 --> 00:16:29.850
When my wife was pregnant
with baby number we were like,

00:16:29.850 --> 00:16:30.850
this is going to be it.

00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:33.690
Third time's a
charm, drama free.

00:16:33.690 --> 00:16:37.262
And instead, she and I ended up
on the front page of "The New

00:16:37.262 --> 00:16:38.470
York Times" business section.

00:16:38.470 --> 00:16:39.722
So here's what happened there.

00:16:39.722 --> 00:16:41.180
My wife was pregnant,
and we looked

00:16:41.180 --> 00:16:42.971
at things that were
going on in our family.

00:16:42.971 --> 00:16:47.480
And we knew that because of her
health and a business, a work

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:48.855
opportunity she
had, that I would

00:16:48.855 --> 00:16:50.521
be needed at home to
do some care giving

00:16:50.521 --> 00:16:51.770
after the baby's birth.

00:16:51.770 --> 00:16:54.190
Now, to all modern couples,
that is a completely

00:16:54.190 --> 00:16:55.717
normal and legitimate concept.

00:16:55.717 --> 00:16:58.300
There's nothing strange about
it and nothing unusual about it.

00:16:58.300 --> 00:17:00.620
More and more men are taking
time to care for our kids.

00:17:00.620 --> 00:17:03.710
Unfortunately, corporate America
has not kept up with this idea.

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:05.760
So I was under this
incredibly weird policy

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:08.630
at CNN under which
anyone can get 10 paid

00:17:08.630 --> 00:17:11.750
weeks to care for their
new baby except a man

00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:14.290
who impregnated his own wife.

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:17.550
So it's as weird as it sounds.

00:17:17.550 --> 00:17:19.798
So I give up my
daughter for adoption,

00:17:19.798 --> 00:17:21.589
and another guy at the
company adopted her,

00:17:21.589 --> 00:17:23.599
he would get 10 paid weeks.

00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:26.710
If we used a surrogate, I
could get 10 paid weeks.

00:17:26.710 --> 00:17:29.510
If I had a same sex
domestic partner

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:32.830
and he adopted a baby but
I did not adopt his baby,

00:17:32.830 --> 00:17:34.820
so I'm not a
co-adoptive parent, I

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:37.700
could still get 10 paid
weeks to care for his baby.

00:17:37.700 --> 00:17:40.440
But I, the real me-- I
couldn't get this time

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:41.320
to care for my baby.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:43.100
So I went to the benefits
department in advance.

00:17:43.100 --> 00:17:45.250
And I was like look, this
was definitely an oversight.

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:46.580
There's no way
you intended this.

00:17:46.580 --> 00:17:48.413
There's no way you meant
for this to happen.

00:17:48.413 --> 00:17:49.470
It's not even possible.

00:17:49.470 --> 00:17:50.590
But they wouldn't
give me an answer.

00:17:50.590 --> 00:17:51.916
And months went by, no answer.

00:17:51.916 --> 00:17:53.290
And then, because
it's my family,

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:54.860
and we can't have
a normal birth,

00:17:54.860 --> 00:17:57.290
my wife went in for her
35 week appointment.

00:17:57.290 --> 00:18:01.720
And she had very scary, serious
symptoms from preeclampsia,

00:18:01.720 --> 00:18:04.820
which even in 2015, if
preeclampsia becomes eclampsia,

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:05.530
it's deadly.

00:18:05.530 --> 00:18:06.030
It's scary.

00:18:06.030 --> 00:18:07.367
So anyway, they had to induce.

00:18:07.367 --> 00:18:09.700
So while we're in the hospital
room, I'm messaging work.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:11.640
Like hey, am I going to
get the 10 weeks or not?

00:18:11.640 --> 00:18:13.620
Because a dad like me
could only get two weeks.

00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:15.310
We were the exception.

00:18:15.310 --> 00:18:17.060
And they wouldn't
give me an answer.

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:20.750
So 11 days later, I'm home,
holding my 4-pound premie,

00:18:20.750 --> 00:18:22.970
and taking care of my
sick wife and my two boys,

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:23.812
and messaging work.

00:18:23.812 --> 00:18:25.270
Am I going back to
work now or not?

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:26.710
And that's when they said no.

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:28.960
That's when they said no,
you cannot have this policy.

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:30.760
No explanation,
just straight up no.

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:32.760
So the rest of the
story's in the book,

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:34.560
but I'm going to tell
you all two things

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:36.040
that I want you
to know right now.

00:18:36.040 --> 00:18:38.110
Oh by the way, so this is
"The New York Times" story.

00:18:38.110 --> 00:18:38.620
Take a look at this though.

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:39.000
It's funny.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:40.230
So I don't really like
that picture of me,

00:18:40.230 --> 00:18:41.620
because I look so angry.

00:18:41.620 --> 00:18:42.952
I look very pensive and angry.

00:18:42.952 --> 00:18:43.660
But look at this.

00:18:43.660 --> 00:18:45.360
They drew this picture.

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:47.820
And this is a Mac computer,
so I forget how you scroll.

00:18:47.820 --> 00:18:49.361
Take a look at the
picture they drew.

00:18:49.361 --> 00:18:50.910
I think that's hilarious.

00:18:50.910 --> 00:18:54.100
To me, that's a much better
summary of the situation

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:56.810
that I was going-- go home.

00:18:56.810 --> 00:18:59.190
So that's "The New
York Times" take on it.

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:00.900
So there are two
things that I want you

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:02.117
to know about what happened.

00:19:02.117 --> 00:19:04.200
And by the way, you can
see how cute she's gotten.

00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:06.470
There she is recently with me.

00:19:06.470 --> 00:19:09.680
So anyway, this was an updated
story that they did recently.

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:12.070
So two things I want you to
know about what happened.

00:19:12.070 --> 00:19:15.410
One is that when we
took this legal action

00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:17.640
against the policy, filing
a charge with the Equal

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:19.306
Employment Opportunity
Commission, which

00:19:19.306 --> 00:19:22.460
is the EEOC, the responses
that came in blew us away,

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:23.034
blew me away.

00:19:23.034 --> 00:19:23.950
I couldn't believe it.

00:19:23.950 --> 00:19:25.544
The responses were
wild, and they

00:19:25.544 --> 00:19:27.835
came in from men's groups
and women's groups, mom blogs

00:19:27.835 --> 00:19:29.909
and dad blogs, from
conservatives and liberals,

00:19:29.909 --> 00:19:32.200
from across the racial
spectrum, the economic spectrum,

00:19:32.200 --> 00:19:33.550
from people across the country.

00:19:33.550 --> 00:19:36.860
So it was like I unleashed
the floodgates of love,

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:38.804
all these people
saying, we support you.

00:19:38.804 --> 00:19:40.470
So as a journalist,
I became fascinated.

00:19:40.470 --> 00:19:42.346
Why do people care about
my family's little--

00:19:42.346 --> 00:19:44.761
I figured there would be some
coverage, but not like that.

00:19:44.761 --> 00:19:46.946
It was huge. "The Today
Show" was talking about us.

00:19:46.946 --> 00:19:48.820
And so I started digging
into these policies.

00:19:48.820 --> 00:19:50.200
What is it about
our situation that's

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:51.460
galvanizing so many people?

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:53.668
And that's when I came to
understand that we are all,

00:19:53.668 --> 00:19:57.859
all in, that everyone who wants
to change the system so we have

00:19:57.859 --> 00:19:59.650
real gender equality
in America, that we're

00:19:59.650 --> 00:20:00.430
all in the same boat.

00:20:00.430 --> 00:20:01.800
There's no gender
war on this stuff.

00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:03.190
We're not fighting
with each other.

00:20:03.190 --> 00:20:04.773
We're all up against
these structures,

00:20:04.773 --> 00:20:07.920
these backward structures that
are holding all of us back.

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:10.000
So that's what I
explore in here.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.270
And this is what I focus on;
laws, workplace policies,

00:20:15.270 --> 00:20:15.910
and stigmas.

00:20:15.910 --> 00:20:17.920
These are the three
categories of things

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:19.160
that need to be fixed.

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:21.620
We have these laws that
stick us in the past.

00:20:21.620 --> 00:20:23.680
We have workplace
policies in many places--

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:25.190
fortunately not here,
as we'll talk about--

00:20:25.190 --> 00:20:27.356
but in many places around
the country that are still

00:20:27.356 --> 00:20:29.560
acting as gender police,
pushing women to stay home,

00:20:29.560 --> 00:20:31.647
pushing men to stay at
work, taking options away.

00:20:31.647 --> 00:20:33.230
And the biggest
problem we have of all

00:20:33.230 --> 00:20:35.610
is stigmas, the
stigmas that are more

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:36.870
powerful than anything else.

00:20:36.870 --> 00:20:37.950
Even if you change
the laws, even

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:39.550
if you change the
policies, you still

00:20:39.550 --> 00:20:44.030
can't end up fixing anything
unless you fix the stigmas.

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:45.824
Now, let's get to
some good news.

00:20:45.824 --> 00:20:47.490
There are a lot of
companies, especially

00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:49.510
out here, in this part of the
country, that are doing really

00:20:49.510 --> 00:20:51.301
well, that have a
policy, and you know this

00:20:51.301 --> 00:20:53.670
very well-- that
have policies that

00:20:53.670 --> 00:20:58.360
are allowing for men and women
to have time to do care giving.

00:20:58.360 --> 00:20:59.540
And that's really important.

00:20:59.540 --> 00:21:02.602
In fact, Google, you
can see right there,

00:21:02.602 --> 00:21:04.310
in the center of that
image, was recently

00:21:04.310 --> 00:21:06.460
named-- this is the new
website called "Fatherly."

00:21:06.460 --> 00:21:07.360
These guys are great.

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:08.230
They've written about my book.

00:21:08.230 --> 00:21:09.600
I've done some pieces for them.

00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:12.190
They wrote "The 50 Best
Places to Work For New Dads."

00:21:12.190 --> 00:21:13.740
He's Google, at number one.

00:21:13.740 --> 00:21:15.275
So what we're seeing
is-- especially

00:21:15.275 --> 00:21:17.900
out in this part of the country,
especially in the tech sector,

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:19.941
in Silicon Valley-- and
you can see some of these

00:21:19.941 --> 00:21:22.080
are also more
traditional businesses.

00:21:22.080 --> 00:21:25.390
But especially out here, in the
valley, in this whole region,

00:21:25.390 --> 00:21:26.850
we have a world.

00:21:26.850 --> 00:21:28.510
We have a set up
in which people are

00:21:28.510 --> 00:21:32.790
able to take time,
whether men or women,

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:34.580
to care for the
children, or if there's

00:21:34.580 --> 00:21:36.010
another kind of care giving.

00:21:36.010 --> 00:21:37.570
But we don't have that in
the rest of the country.

00:21:37.570 --> 00:21:39.030
This way of thinking
has not caught

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:40.970
on in the rest of the country.

00:21:40.970 --> 00:21:42.530
So we have that problem.

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:44.531
And then we also have the
problem with our laws.

00:21:44.531 --> 00:21:46.030
Now, I mentioned
earlier that we are

00:21:46.030 --> 00:21:48.570
the only country that doesn't
have any paid maternity leave.

00:21:48.570 --> 00:21:50.230
But no one ever talks about why.

00:21:50.230 --> 00:21:52.680
When I came to understand this,
suddenly I understood why.

00:21:52.680 --> 00:21:55.630
The reason we don't have
this is so obvious to me now.

00:21:55.630 --> 00:21:58.430
It's that our work culture is
based on that old mentality.

00:21:58.430 --> 00:22:01.810
So why would we possibly
need to pay women?

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:02.414
She's a woman.

00:22:02.414 --> 00:22:03.580
She's supposed to stay home.

00:22:03.580 --> 00:22:04.600
Who needs her money?

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:06.414
That's the thinking
behind all of it.

00:22:06.414 --> 00:22:08.080
And the thinking for
men is why would he

00:22:08.080 --> 00:22:09.660
possibly need paternity leave?

00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:10.290
He's a man.

00:22:10.290 --> 00:22:12.350
His role is to stay at work.

00:22:12.350 --> 00:22:15.481
It's easy to think that we've
come a long way, as a nation.

00:22:15.481 --> 00:22:17.980
But then there was an article
recently in "The Miami Herald"

00:22:17.980 --> 00:22:19.580
in which they interviewed
a bunch of CEOs.

00:22:19.580 --> 00:22:22.120
And they asked people just about
the concept of paternity leave.

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:23.220
It was just a
straight up question.

00:22:23.220 --> 00:22:24.969
What are your thoughts
on paternity leave?

00:22:24.969 --> 00:22:27.105
And several CEOs said
it should never exist.

00:22:27.105 --> 00:22:28.980
And one of them said,
no only if the woman is

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:32.580
physically incapacitated, which
brings us to the next part.

00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:34.700
So we got the laws
and the policies.

00:22:34.700 --> 00:22:38.920
But by far, the biggest problem
that we have are the stigmas.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:40.490
Men are punished
in the workplace,

00:22:40.490 --> 00:22:41.948
in all these
traditional workplace.

00:22:41.948 --> 00:22:43.474
It happens a lot
for taking time off

00:22:43.474 --> 00:22:44.640
for any kind of care giving.

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:46.960
And the stories that I have from
these guys are heartbreaking,

00:22:46.960 --> 00:22:48.293
and you'll see them in the book.

00:22:48.293 --> 00:22:50.280
It's wild what
they've gone through.

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:52.710
This one man was
refused the time

00:22:52.710 --> 00:22:55.714
that he's legally entitled
to because his boss told him,

00:22:55.714 --> 00:22:57.630
women are supposed to
take care of the babies,

00:22:57.630 --> 00:22:59.390
unless they're in
a coma or dead.

00:22:59.390 --> 00:23:00.544
That's what his boss said.

00:23:00.544 --> 00:23:02.960
Another thing I have in the
book was I got a call at work.

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:04.982
His wife was really scared.

00:23:04.982 --> 00:23:06.190
They were both really scared.

00:23:06.190 --> 00:23:07.564
The placenta had
stopped working.

00:23:07.564 --> 00:23:08.540
She was at 37 weeks.

00:23:08.540 --> 00:23:09.540
The baby wasn't moving.

00:23:09.540 --> 00:23:11.270
They needed to
induce right away.

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:13.170
By the way, if anybody watching
this is pregnant, don't worry.

00:23:13.170 --> 00:23:14.640
This is all very, very unusual.

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:16.400
It's not going to happen to you.

00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:18.802
But extremely-- all of it,
it's a lot of horror stories

00:23:18.802 --> 00:23:19.760
that I've had to learn.

00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:21.950
So anyway, so he got this
call, and he ran out.

00:23:21.950 --> 00:23:23.680
He just missed the
rest of that day

00:23:23.680 --> 00:23:24.971
and then the rest of that week.

00:23:24.971 --> 00:23:26.654
So he just missed
two days after that,

00:23:26.654 --> 00:23:27.820
came back to work on Monday.

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:29.770
His boss called him
in and rebuked him.

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:31.575
How dare you take
off so much time?

00:23:31.575 --> 00:23:33.460
Don't you know you're
needed around here?

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:36.661
And that boss was a pregnant
woman, which surprised me

00:23:36.661 --> 00:23:38.910
when I first heard it and
surprises some other people,

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:40.576
but it does not
surprise the lawyers who

00:23:40.576 --> 00:23:43.520
are leading this fight,
because these lawyers know

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:45.836
that there are gender police
who are men and women.

00:23:45.836 --> 00:23:48.460
And the thinking for some women
who are acting as gender police

00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:49.420
is well, wait a second.

00:23:49.420 --> 00:23:50.940
I'm a woman, so
I'll take time off.

00:23:50.940 --> 00:23:51.560
But you're a man.

00:23:51.560 --> 00:23:52.726
Why would you need time off?

00:23:52.726 --> 00:23:54.154
You're supposed to stay home!

00:23:54.154 --> 00:23:55.070
That's the whole idea.

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:56.950
That's what men do.

00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:59.440
So these are the kinds of things
that I talk about in here.

00:23:59.440 --> 00:24:01.106
But I said earlier,
there are two things

00:24:01.106 --> 00:24:03.589
I want you to know about how
I took on this legal action.

00:24:03.589 --> 00:24:04.380
That was the first.

00:24:04.380 --> 00:24:07.670
The second is that as
a result, the company

00:24:07.670 --> 00:24:10.560
revolutionized its policy and
made it much, much better.

00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:12.640
I knew that I was fighting
for a better business.

00:24:12.640 --> 00:24:14.980
I knew that a better policy--
because I'd been covering this,

00:24:14.980 --> 00:24:16.680
and I'd been covering
economies around the world.

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:17.596
I knew how this works.

00:24:17.596 --> 00:24:19.261
I knew that it's
better for businesses

00:24:19.261 --> 00:24:20.260
to have better policies.

00:24:20.260 --> 00:24:21.926
You attract and retain
better employees,

00:24:21.926 --> 00:24:23.120
as you very well know.

00:24:23.120 --> 00:24:24.640
It helps you compete.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:26.540
The company, if
you ask them, they

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:29.030
will tell you that the change
they made to the policy,

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:31.370
it was a win-win, that it
worked really well for them.

00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:32.954
There was so much
coverage in my case.

00:24:32.954 --> 00:24:34.161
People were talking about it.

00:24:34.161 --> 00:24:36.040
The company obviously
heard the rallying cry.

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:38.206
And they said, we've got
to do something about this.

00:24:38.206 --> 00:24:40.530
So now, men and
women get more time,

00:24:40.530 --> 00:24:41.620
as a result of the change.

00:24:41.620 --> 00:24:43.200
What they did was
before, a dad like

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:44.366
me could only get two weeks.

00:24:44.366 --> 00:24:46.680
Now, a dad like me can
get six paid weeks.

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:49.240
Women now get paid
their six weeks

00:24:49.240 --> 00:24:51.770
for care giving on
top of their time

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:54.360
for physical recovery, which
is what businesses are supposed

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:55.943
to do, according to
federal guideline,

00:24:55.943 --> 00:24:58.530
separate physical recovery
time from care giving time.

00:24:58.530 --> 00:24:59.570
So women are getting
the six weeks

00:24:59.570 --> 00:25:01.490
of care giving leave,
plus six or eight weeks,

00:25:01.490 --> 00:25:03.364
depending on the kind
of birth that they had.

00:25:03.364 --> 00:25:04.980
So the company now
has a better policy

00:25:04.980 --> 00:25:08.390
that's paid off for
just about everybody.

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:10.900
But while we are
seeing these changes,

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:12.390
we're not seeing enough of them.

00:25:12.390 --> 00:25:16.090
And there are two big ways
that we need to fix this.

00:25:16.090 --> 00:25:18.762
One is we need to do
something about the lies,

00:25:18.762 --> 00:25:20.970
because as long as people
believe that dads are lazy,

00:25:20.970 --> 00:25:22.700
that dads don't do anything,
that dads aren't helping

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:24.991
with their families, people
who believe that will never

00:25:24.991 --> 00:25:27.590
support paternity leave,
will never support equality.

00:25:27.590 --> 00:25:29.750
Unfortunately my
industry, journalism,

00:25:29.750 --> 00:25:31.010
keeps blowing it all the time.

00:25:31.010 --> 00:25:32.260
And this is a perfect example.

00:25:32.260 --> 00:25:35.400
So Pew Research has messed
up a lot of stuff on this.

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:37.650
But in my industry, I've
spent 10 years at NPR,

00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:39.669
10 years at CNN,
everyone goes by Pew,

00:25:39.669 --> 00:25:40.710
no matter what they said.

00:25:40.710 --> 00:25:41.760
So this is an example.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:44.050
Pew Research wrote this.
"Another Gender Gap-- Men

00:25:44.050 --> 00:25:45.720
Spend More Time in
Leisure Activities."

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:47.201
And then, as a
result of that, you

00:25:47.201 --> 00:25:48.950
have all of these not
obnoxious headlines.

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:51.360
The leisure gap-- why
women are losing their time

00:25:51.360 --> 00:25:52.162
to just chill out.

00:25:52.162 --> 00:25:53.870
Men have more time
for fun than women do.

00:25:53.870 --> 00:25:54.980
And this is the
worst one of all.

00:25:54.980 --> 00:25:56.040
I found this from "Time."

00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:57.270
The moral of the
story, whether it's

00:25:57.270 --> 00:25:58.644
the week day or
the weekend, dads

00:25:58.644 --> 00:26:01.380
need to spend less time on the
golf course and watching TV,

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:03.670
and more time helping their
wives take out the trash

00:26:03.670 --> 00:26:06.620
and play with the kids; those
naughty, lazy, lame dads.

00:26:06.620 --> 00:26:08.290
If you believed
this, you would never

00:26:08.290 --> 00:26:10.220
ever support the idea
of a man staying home,

00:26:10.220 --> 00:26:11.469
because what's he going to do?

00:26:11.469 --> 00:26:13.650
He's going to sit around
till his wife gets home.

00:26:13.650 --> 00:26:15.470
Here's what the
research actually says.

00:26:15.470 --> 00:26:18.120
Pew Research looked at something
called the American Time Use

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:18.619
Survey.

00:26:18.619 --> 00:26:19.690
This is government data.

00:26:19.690 --> 00:26:22.590
In this survey,
dads interviewed,

00:26:22.590 --> 00:26:24.390
they broke down what
a typical day is like.

00:26:24.390 --> 00:26:28.340
Dads listed 20 more minutes as
being for leisure or sports.

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:31.790
What Pew did not mention is
that moms listed 20 more minutes

00:26:31.790 --> 00:26:34.100
as being for sleep.

00:26:34.100 --> 00:26:36.242
What we actually have
is an incredible parity.

00:26:36.242 --> 00:26:38.450
We've achieved a kind of a
egalitarianism in the home

00:26:38.450 --> 00:26:39.920
that no one realizes
we have, because there

00:26:39.920 --> 00:26:41.920
are all these obnoxious
headlines out there that

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:43.930
make people think that
this is about gender war.

00:26:43.930 --> 00:26:45.840
It makes people think that if
the men would just stay up,

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:46.923
everything would be fixed.

00:26:46.923 --> 00:26:49.480
But the men and the women
today are all in this together,

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:51.550
and this is the reality.

00:26:51.550 --> 00:26:53.140
Unfortunately, I've tried.

00:26:53.140 --> 00:26:54.780
I tried to get
Per to correct it.

00:26:54.780 --> 00:26:57.180
I've contacted news agencies
that wrote these headlines.

00:26:57.180 --> 00:26:59.630
And so far, it's not
getting anywhere.

00:26:59.630 --> 00:27:02.090
So this is how I feel every
time I see this pop up again.

00:27:02.090 --> 00:27:04.030
I love gifs, by the way.

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:05.960
So I explain in the
book, and I want

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:06.950
to show you this
one part that it's

00:27:06.950 --> 00:27:09.158
really important for everyone
watching to understand.

00:27:09.158 --> 00:27:11.500
"Today's dads and
moms work equally

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:12.819
on behalf of their families.

00:27:12.819 --> 00:27:15.235
When you combine paid work
with household chores and child

00:27:15.235 --> 00:27:17.760
care, they put in just about
the same amount of time."

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:19.430
And this is true in
every combination.

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:22.880
If you have a working father and
a stay-at-home mom, a working

00:27:22.880 --> 00:27:25.260
mom and a stay-at-home
dad, two working parents--

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:27.640
in every combination
you have overall,

00:27:27.640 --> 00:27:30.960
the amount of time being put
in on behalf of your family

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:32.217
is the same.

00:27:32.217 --> 00:27:34.300
People have an equal
commitment to their families.

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:37.957
Now, moms spend more of those
hours at home, on average.

00:27:37.957 --> 00:27:39.540
And that has to do
with these stigmas.

00:27:39.540 --> 00:27:41.340
They're the stigmas that men
are facing in the workplace,

00:27:41.340 --> 00:27:43.548
and then women are facing
stigmas in both directions.

00:27:43.548 --> 00:27:44.350
It's awful.

00:27:44.350 --> 00:27:46.439
Some women lose
work opportunities

00:27:46.439 --> 00:27:48.730
because they have bosses who
think they should be home,

00:27:48.730 --> 00:27:50.070
because they're women.

00:27:50.070 --> 00:27:52.370
So there are many
studies that show this.

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:55.365
If a man whose a boss has
two employees, one's a dad,

00:27:55.365 --> 00:27:57.740
one's a mom, and there's a
really important project which

00:27:57.740 --> 00:28:00.689
is a great opportunity, then
often he will say to the woman,

00:28:00.689 --> 00:28:01.480
no, no, no, no, no.

00:28:01.480 --> 00:28:02.330
You go home.

00:28:02.330 --> 00:28:03.070
He's got this.

00:28:03.569 --> 00:28:05.700
So women are losing out
on opportunities that way.

00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:07.300
But then women are
also getting jobs

00:28:07.300 --> 00:28:08.760
just the way men
are when they do

00:28:08.760 --> 00:28:11.040
have caregiving
responsibilities, which

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:13.090
is why it's so good to
be here because places

00:28:13.090 --> 00:28:16.110
that are changing the culture
are what we need more of.

00:28:16.110 --> 00:28:17.720
So this is part of this.

00:28:17.720 --> 00:28:22.140
But another big thing we need
in this country and, ultimately,

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:23.920
the best thing we
can do to fix this

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:26.640
is to establish laws that
make clear to everyone

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:28.404
that men and women
can be caregivers

00:28:28.404 --> 00:28:29.820
and that it will
benefit everyone.

00:28:29.820 --> 00:28:31.330
And the good news is that
we already have this.

00:28:31.330 --> 00:28:32.310
We're in California right now.

00:28:32.310 --> 00:28:33.850
This is one of the
places that has.

00:28:33.850 --> 00:28:35.420
Three states have
this-- paid family

00:28:35.420 --> 00:28:40.217
leave policies, which are run
by a public system and not

00:28:40.217 --> 00:28:42.300
by individual businesses--
California, New Jersey,

00:28:42.300 --> 00:28:43.411
Rhode Island.

00:28:43.411 --> 00:28:45.410
I've looked at a lot of
policies over the years.

00:28:45.410 --> 00:28:46.360
I've covered the stimulus.

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:47.950
I've covered so much
about businesses.

00:28:47.950 --> 00:28:50.910
I've never seen as successful
a policy in general

00:28:50.910 --> 00:28:52.100
for businesses as this.

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:54.490
The way it works is it
operates as an insurance policy

00:28:54.490 --> 00:28:57.070
so people pay a tiny
little bit of their payroll

00:28:57.070 --> 00:28:58.000
into this fund.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.690
That fund then pays you if you
need six weeks of paid family

00:29:01.690 --> 00:29:03.696
leave, and this is not
just caring for a child.

00:29:03.696 --> 00:29:05.570
You can see the picture
I chose to use there.

00:29:05.570 --> 00:29:07.569
This is caring for an
elderly parent or a spouse

00:29:07.569 --> 00:29:09.870
or yourself after an illness.

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:11.780
All these things are covered.

00:29:11.780 --> 00:29:13.670
And what places
have started to find

00:29:13.670 --> 00:29:16.110
is that when they have
these public policies,

00:29:16.110 --> 00:29:18.569
women will take time off
and then so will men.

00:29:18.569 --> 00:29:20.110
And these businesses
have been forced

00:29:20.110 --> 00:29:22.039
to see that a man can
take time off and then

00:29:22.039 --> 00:29:24.080
come back to work and be
just as good an employee

00:29:24.080 --> 00:29:25.290
as he was before.

00:29:25.290 --> 00:29:29.236
So this new idea needs
to catch on nationally,

00:29:29.236 --> 00:29:31.110
and this is what we're
pushing for right now.

