I have a way for
you to contact me.

00:36:51.140 --> 00:36:56.378
I use everything,
including Google+.

00:36:56.378 --> 00:36:57.660
I encourage you all.

00:36:57.660 --> 00:37:00.082
There you go.

00:37:00.082 --> 00:37:01.290
That's the way to contact me.

00:37:01.290 --> 00:37:02.620
I love to hear from everybody.

00:37:02.620 --> 00:37:03.740
And also I link
in with everyone.

00:37:03.740 --> 00:37:05.120
They say not to link
in with everyone.

00:37:05.120 --> 00:37:06.240
They say, only link in
with people you know.

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:07.160
I don't know why they say that.

00:37:07.160 --> 00:37:08.420
I link in with
absolutely everyone.

00:37:08.420 --> 00:37:09.044
Did we link in?

00:37:09.044 --> 00:37:10.060
We linked in, right?

00:37:10.060 --> 00:37:10.650
Didn't we?

00:37:10.650 --> 00:37:12.841
Well, we need to.

00:37:12.841 --> 00:37:14.340
AUDIENCE: Maybe a
two-part question.

00:37:14.340 --> 00:37:16.490
One is, is this your
full-time thing now?

00:37:16.490 --> 00:37:17.990
And at what point
in the journey did

00:37:17.990 --> 00:37:20.974
you recognize this
could be-- assuming

00:37:20.974 --> 00:37:22.640
that's the answer--
the full-time thing.

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:23.790
JOSH LEVS: Yeah, I'm now
doing this full time.

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:25.050
Yeah it's wild what happened.

00:37:25.050 --> 00:37:27.110
My book came out
in May, and we were

00:37:27.110 --> 00:37:30.189
hoping that it would
get some people talking.

00:37:30.189 --> 00:37:32.230
And fortunately, the
response has been incredible

00:37:32.230 --> 00:37:33.760
just in terms of
getting invited places

00:37:33.760 --> 00:37:34.801
to talk about this issue.

00:37:34.801 --> 00:37:36.730
People want to hear
about the issue.

00:37:36.730 --> 00:37:38.670
So, yes, I recently
officially left CNN

00:37:38.670 --> 00:37:40.837
because I was on leave, and
it was during the book--

00:37:40.837 --> 00:37:42.753
and now I'm booked all
the way through the end

00:37:42.753 --> 00:37:43.970
of the year with events.

00:37:43.970 --> 00:37:47.010
So I'm happy to, yeah, say
I'm doing this full time.

00:37:47.010 --> 00:37:49.100
And it's working
out well so far.

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:51.180
Now, fortunately, I get
to come places like here

00:37:51.180 --> 00:37:53.490
and meet people this week in
San Francisco was amazing.

00:37:53.490 --> 00:37:56.320
I spoke at Twitter and
Nerd Wallet and Stanford,

00:37:56.320 --> 00:37:58.509
and I'm doing a big
conference keynote tomorrow.

00:37:58.509 --> 00:37:59.800
And on Friday, I'm going to GE.

00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:00.800
So there's a lot
of places I want

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:01.970
to have these conversations.

00:38:01.970 --> 00:38:03.360
I just got back from
Austin where I was

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:04.490
working with Liberty Mutual.

00:38:04.490 --> 00:38:05.948
They're doing all
this great stuff.

00:38:05.948 --> 00:38:07.590
So, yes, it is.

00:38:07.590 --> 00:38:09.390
And when did I realize it.

00:38:09.390 --> 00:38:11.049
I knew it could
be an opportunity,

00:38:11.049 --> 00:38:12.840
but I didn't know until
this book came out,

00:38:12.840 --> 00:38:14.540
and I started getting
all these invitations

00:38:14.540 --> 00:38:15.665
that it could be full time.

00:38:15.665 --> 00:38:17.760
So I would say probably
like August, September,

00:38:17.760 --> 00:38:21.370
I started to realize that
this can go somewhere along.

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:23.550
And the great thing
is now I travel.

00:38:23.550 --> 00:38:25.959
So I could be this
massive hypocrite.

00:38:25.959 --> 00:38:27.000
Family time is important.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:28.960
I say, well, I
travel all the time.

00:38:28.960 --> 00:38:31.996
So I try to pack all my travel
into four days at a time,

00:38:31.996 --> 00:38:33.370
and then when I'm
home, I'm home.

00:38:33.370 --> 00:38:34.940
Because I'm not rushing off
to a job in the morning.

00:38:34.940 --> 00:38:36.650
So I'm taking the kids
to school, and I'm there,

00:38:36.650 --> 00:38:38.566
and we're playing, and
we're doing everything.

00:38:38.566 --> 00:38:41.610
So, so far, I'm managing to
find the balance that way.

00:38:41.610 --> 00:38:42.750
But we'll see.

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:46.800
I just also disbelieve in taking
steps forward and believing

00:38:46.800 --> 00:38:49.100
that there will be
solid ground under me

00:38:49.100 --> 00:38:53.470
and not worry about what
if it all falls apart.

00:38:53.470 --> 00:38:54.580
AUDIENCE: Wonderful.

00:38:54.580 --> 00:38:57.450
JOSH LEVS: Thanks.

00:38:57.450 --> 00:38:58.490
Yeah?

00:38:58.490 --> 00:38:58.990
Yeah, sure.

00:39:02.340 --> 00:39:05.450
AUDIENCE: So you gave props to
the Silicon Valley companies

00:39:05.450 --> 00:39:07.090
for leading the
way in this area.

00:39:07.090 --> 00:39:08.590
JOSH LEVS: A bunch of them.

00:39:08.590 --> 00:39:12.480
AUDIENCE: But they're also
notorious for people going

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:13.930
and not taking their vacations.

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:15.550
They're just falling
off the edge.

00:39:15.550 --> 00:39:18.917
So what's the interplay
with those two things?

00:39:18.917 --> 00:39:20.250
JOSH LEVS: That is all top down.

00:39:20.250 --> 00:39:22.010
I'm glad you asked about that.

00:39:22.010 --> 00:39:25.070
One problem out here is that
people mythologize overworking.

00:39:25.070 --> 00:39:27.389
And it's important not to
mythologize overworking.

00:39:27.389 --> 00:39:29.430
Not to be like, oh, that's
such a great employee.

00:39:29.430 --> 00:39:30.685
He works 20 hours a day.

00:39:30.685 --> 00:39:32.310
That doesn't make
him a great employee.

00:39:32.310 --> 00:39:34.060
He might be a great
employee and overwork,

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:37.320
but those two things
are coincidences.

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:39.947
And so it has to be
top down, and that's

00:39:39.947 --> 00:39:41.030
the same thing with leave.

00:39:41.030 --> 00:39:42.863
Like a lot of people
now have been asking me

00:39:42.863 --> 00:39:44.364
about Marissa Mayer
at Yahoo who has

00:39:44.364 --> 00:39:46.946
said that after she has twins,
she is going to take off, what?

00:39:46.946 --> 00:39:47.987
A couple weeks, I think.

00:39:47.987 --> 00:39:49.570
I'm keeping an eye
on Mark Zuckerberg.

00:39:49.570 --> 00:39:51.110
They have 17 paid weeks there.

00:39:51.110 --> 00:39:52.070
I hope he takes them.

00:39:52.070 --> 00:39:53.903
And a lot of people
think he probably won't.

00:39:53.903 --> 00:39:55.900
And the problem is
that it's all top down.

00:39:55.900 --> 00:39:58.610
So when policy is on
paper, it doesn't matter.

00:39:58.610 --> 00:40:00.400
What matters is what
happens in practice.

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:04.160
So what we need is to have
leaders who take vacations

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:06.710
as allowed and actual
vacations, so they're not

00:40:06.710 --> 00:40:07.840
working on their vacations.

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:09.530
And I explain it here
that's also proven out

00:40:09.530 --> 00:40:11.110
to be good for business
because it helps

00:40:11.110 --> 00:40:12.210
other people have opportunity.

00:40:12.210 --> 00:40:14.085
You're nodding your head
you know about this.

00:40:14.085 --> 00:40:16.700
It's proven now that it helps
other people work their way up.

00:40:16.700 --> 00:40:19.270
There's some grandparents
in the book grandads,

00:40:19.270 --> 00:40:22.280
who did it the old, traditional
way when they had their kids.

00:40:22.280 --> 00:40:23.950
And now, they want
to do it this way.

00:40:23.950 --> 00:40:26.310
So they are taking care of
their grandkids one or two

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:27.110
days a week.

00:40:27.110 --> 00:40:29.050
And they've shrunk their
work schedules because of it.

00:40:29.050 --> 00:40:30.730
And the couple from in
here explained to me

00:40:30.730 --> 00:40:32.950
that they have now learned
what they learned decades

00:40:32.950 --> 00:40:34.994
ago which is that when
they take those days off,

00:40:34.994 --> 00:40:37.160
they're really not working,
and when they come back,

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:40.340
everything's fine because their
underlings were given the trust

00:40:40.340 --> 00:40:41.620
to really get things done.

00:40:41.620 --> 00:40:44.080
It wasn't you have to call me
if anything at all comes up,

00:40:44.080 --> 00:40:46.580
and the people who work there
understand that for that day,

00:40:46.580 --> 00:40:48.060
someone else really
is in charge.

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:50.601
It gives other people a chance
to work their way up and learn

00:40:50.601 --> 00:40:51.390
the business.

00:40:51.390 --> 00:40:53.094
So long-winded
answer your question,

00:40:53.094 --> 00:40:54.260
but it's all about top down.

00:40:54.260 --> 00:40:55.420
We have to make this
happen top down.

00:40:55.420 --> 00:40:56.628
That's the only way to do it.

00:40:56.628 --> 00:40:57.788
Yeah, go ahead.

00:40:57.788 --> 00:40:58.800
AUDIENCE: Actually, OK.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:00.550
JOSH LEVS: OK, I saw
you nodding your head

00:41:00.550 --> 00:41:03.520
so maybe that-- were you
wondering about all the travel

00:41:03.520 --> 00:41:04.880
and stuff?

00:41:04.880 --> 00:41:05.630
You're like, yeah.

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:06.576
AUDIENCE: I was going
to ask you about that,

00:41:06.576 --> 00:41:07.380
but you answered it.

00:41:07.380 --> 00:41:08.780
JOSH LEVS: You were going
to ask me about why do I

00:41:08.780 --> 00:41:10.290
talk about-- yeah, it's crazy.

00:41:10.290 --> 00:41:13.470
Like, here I am 3,000 miles
away from my kids, right?

00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:15.200
And we Skype when we can.

00:41:15.200 --> 00:41:17.240
Although I was also
explaining earlier that

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:20.200
my kids' favorite thing is
not Skype or Facebook video.

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:21.800
It's Google Hangout
video because I

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:23.520
get to put those faces on.

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:24.520
Have you guys done this.

00:41:24.520 --> 00:41:27.110
You can press buttons and make
these faces appear on you.

00:41:27.110 --> 00:41:28.210
I'm such a Google fanboy.

00:41:28.210 --> 00:41:29.722
It's good to be here.

00:41:29.722 --> 00:41:31.430
Yeah, and baby was
saying to me yesterday

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:33.080
when we were on Facebook videos.

00:41:33.080 --> 00:41:34.740
She was like funny
face, funny face.

00:41:34.740 --> 00:41:35.910
And I said, I can't do it.

00:41:35.910 --> 00:41:36.460
I'm sorry.

00:41:36.460 --> 00:41:38.184
We're not I Google
Hangout right now.

00:41:38.184 --> 00:41:40.850
So I need your Google Hangout to
create those tools for my phone

00:41:40.850 --> 00:41:43.691
so I could do it on my phone too
and not just on my Chromebook.

00:41:43.691 --> 00:41:45.010
Go ahead.

00:41:45.010 --> 00:41:46.660
AUDIENCE: I have
another question.

00:41:46.660 --> 00:41:49.610
So you speak at all of
these different places.

00:41:49.610 --> 00:41:53.620
I'm curious what's the most
resistance you've faced

00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:56.340
and how you've turned it around.

00:41:56.340 --> 00:42:00.230
JOSH LEVS: So the good news
is that partly because I'm

00:42:00.230 --> 00:42:03.590
a communicator, I know how to
knock down a lot of those walls

00:42:03.590 --> 00:42:04.670
when I get somewhere.

00:42:04.670 --> 00:42:07.169
You know, when I spoke with the
National Chamber of Commerce

00:42:07.169 --> 00:42:09.740
in New Hampshire-- a mostly
conservative organization--

00:42:09.740 --> 00:42:11.942
traditional views on how
a lot of things work,

00:42:11.942 --> 00:42:12.900
but not so much gender.

00:42:12.900 --> 00:42:14.441
They want women to
work their way up.

00:42:14.441 --> 00:42:17.035
But the places like that get
afraid that I'm to come in

00:42:17.035 --> 00:42:19.160
and say, oh, businesses
have to pay for everything.

00:42:19.160 --> 00:42:21.046
It's all up to businesses.

00:42:21.046 --> 00:42:23.420
So I start off my talk to
explain that my grandfather was

00:42:23.420 --> 00:42:24.836
a small business
owner that he had

00:42:24.836 --> 00:42:26.462
a tiny shop at the
edge of his driveway

00:42:26.462 --> 00:42:28.502
that I've always understood
the importance of not

00:42:28.502 --> 00:42:30.090
over-regulating
businesses, and that I

00:42:30.090 --> 00:42:31.100
want businesses to thrive.

00:42:31.100 --> 00:42:32.600
And then they start
listening to me.

00:42:32.600 --> 00:42:35.030
The most pushback
I have ever had

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:37.257
is one place that I won't
name that was supposed

00:42:37.257 --> 00:42:39.340
to give a talk at, and
they told me that they had,

00:42:39.340 --> 00:42:41.400
I think, I like about
100 people signed up,

00:42:41.400 --> 00:42:44.634
and then HR got
involved, and they

00:42:44.634 --> 00:42:47.050
wanted me to jump through all
these hoops to even show up.

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:48.216
Like, what are going to say?

00:42:48.216 --> 00:42:50.115
What are you going to not say?

00:42:50.115 --> 00:42:51.740
And I explained I'm
not a Trojan horse.

00:42:51.740 --> 00:42:54.240
I don't go to companies to try
to blow up their own policies

00:42:54.240 --> 00:42:56.787
from the inside.

00:42:56.787 --> 00:42:58.370
But it wasn't even
about them anymore.

00:42:58.370 --> 00:42:59.830
It was like this and this
and this and this and this,

00:42:59.830 --> 00:43:01.788
and by the way, you can't
talk about your book.

00:43:01.788 --> 00:43:05.370
So I said, no, look,
it's not worth it

00:43:05.370 --> 00:43:07.120
for me to make the
trek out there.

00:43:07.120 --> 00:43:09.540
So there are places
that still have

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:14.270
that that are so afraid of
someone coming in and saying

00:43:14.270 --> 00:43:18.090
anything that might in any
way make them look imperfect.

00:43:18.090 --> 00:43:20.547
But people respect
their businesses

00:43:20.547 --> 00:43:23.130
for being self-effacing and for
having conversations and being

00:43:23.130 --> 00:43:24.850
open to new ideas.

00:43:24.850 --> 00:43:28.680
But this is a business that
is traditional and still has

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:29.720
backward policies.

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:31.700
So there's that.

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:33.210
I also wrote a piece
slamming Amazon

00:43:33.210 --> 00:43:35.790
for having no paternity leave,
which is disgusting, one

00:43:35.790 --> 00:43:38.984
of the many problems at
Amazon, unacceptable, no.

00:43:38.984 --> 00:43:40.650
Anyone know people
at Amazon, call them.

00:43:40.650 --> 00:43:42.810
Tell them to do
something about it.

00:43:42.810 --> 00:43:45.580
AUDIENCE: So it's kind of
like a prediction thing.

00:43:45.580 --> 00:43:49.110
If you have a crystal ball, and
you're to look forward again

00:43:49.110 --> 00:43:51.230
at the US in 10
years, do you think

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:54.050
there would be a federal
mandated paternity leave?

00:43:54.050 --> 00:43:55.230
And how long would that be?

00:43:55.230 --> 00:43:58.020
JOSH LEVS: Yeah, with the paid
family leave that we need,

00:43:58.020 --> 00:43:59.700
I'm hoping within 10 years.

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:02.580
So we've got unpaid leave 1993,
which was called the Family

00:44:02.580 --> 00:44:03.400
Medical Leave Act.

00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:05.850
But it doesn't apply
to 40% of workers,

00:44:05.850 --> 00:44:09.240
and even 1 in 5 companies
admit they don't even fully

00:44:09.240 --> 00:44:10.480
comply with the law.

00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:14.265
So this idea of what we need
now being paid family leave.

00:44:14.265 --> 00:44:16.140
I think you've actually
got the figure right.

00:44:16.140 --> 00:44:18.590
My hope is that within
10 years, we get it.

00:44:18.590 --> 00:44:21.420
The problem is
messaging to people

00:44:21.420 --> 00:44:24.670
who are afraid of anything
that has the word tax in it

00:44:24.670 --> 00:44:26.860
because even though it's
so good for everyone,

00:44:26.860 --> 00:44:28.984
it's proven in three
states, some people

00:44:28.984 --> 00:44:30.900
just won't support it
because of the word tax.

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:33.317
The problem is that we cannot
do a state-by-state solution

00:44:33.317 --> 00:44:35.941
because most states don't have
a structure to collect the money

00:44:35.941 --> 00:44:36.691
and distribute it.

00:44:36.691 --> 00:44:39.190
Like Washington State passed
paid family leave several years

00:44:39.190 --> 00:44:40.670
ago, but they still
don't have it,

00:44:40.670 --> 00:44:41.750
because they don't
have-- I don't even

00:44:41.750 --> 00:44:42.760
know why they passed it.

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:44.610
They created it, but
don't have a structure.

00:44:44.610 --> 00:44:46.070
They don't have a
bureaucracy in the way

00:44:46.070 --> 00:44:47.900
that the state works that
would take in the money

00:44:47.900 --> 00:44:48.649
and distribute it.

00:44:48.649 --> 00:44:50.100
So we need a national policy.

00:44:50.100 --> 00:44:52.570
So my hope is that
within the next 10 years,

00:44:52.570 --> 00:44:55.260
the Democrats are
talking about it.

00:44:55.260 --> 00:44:57.490
Almost all the Democrats
running for president right

00:44:57.490 --> 00:44:59.592
now are lining up for it.

00:44:59.592 --> 00:45:01.550
But in order to get
something through Congress,

00:45:01.550 --> 00:45:03.133
it would need some
bipartisan support.

00:45:03.133 --> 00:45:04.930
So it's just a handful
of brave Republicans

00:45:04.930 --> 00:45:06.620
who will step
forward and say, yes.

00:45:06.620 --> 00:45:07.889
Jim Daly is in here.

00:45:07.889 --> 00:45:09.930
He's the head of Focus on
the Family, a staunchly

00:45:09.930 --> 00:45:11.340
conservative organization.

00:45:11.340 --> 00:45:14.470
He says in here, I opposed
FMLA, Family Medical Leave Act.

00:45:14.470 --> 00:45:15.280
I'm embarrassed.

00:45:15.280 --> 00:45:16.610
We should never have
been against it.

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:18.240
Conservatives should
have supported it.

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:19.260
I'm open to new things.

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:20.990
A bunch of Republicans
are in here.

00:45:20.990 --> 00:45:23.150
3/4 of Republican voters
want a paid family

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:24.830
leave insurance policy.

00:45:24.830 --> 00:45:27.790
So it's not really about
the general broad base.

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:30.170
It's about lawmakers
who are worried

00:45:30.170 --> 00:45:32.910
about their extreme voters in
gerrymandered districts, who

00:45:32.910 --> 00:45:35.270
will just hear the word
tax and go the other way.

00:45:35.270 --> 00:45:38.074
So my hope is that in
10 years, we'll get it.

00:45:38.074 --> 00:45:40.740
And I'm enough of an optimist to
believe that, yes, in 10 years,

00:45:40.740 --> 00:45:43.050
we will have a federal
plan that makes--

00:45:43.050 --> 00:45:44.780
and I want to understand
the stakes here.

00:45:44.780 --> 00:45:45.870
I mean, for everything
that happened

00:45:45.870 --> 00:45:48.078
with me-- for everything
I'm talking about-- the fact

00:45:48.078 --> 00:45:50.349
that right now we are
tearing away parents

00:45:50.349 --> 00:45:52.640
